defaultC. 
defaultWhat are the main challenges associated with providing better and more consistent bus and rail 
defaultservices to isolated communiti
defaultes? How can these challenges be 
defaultovercome?
defaultOne challenge on 
defaulta few rail
default routes is to be able to offer a frequency of service adequate to meet the various needs of people in the communities it serves.  A few rural railway routes 
defaultoffer a service of just four trains a day each way, which limits 
defaultjourney 
defaultopportunities.  
defaultThe lines concerned are:
defaultIn the case of Esk Valley, for example, the timetable is built around the need to bring schoolchildren to Whitby from the villages along the Esk Valley, and to bring in day trip visi
defaultt
defaultors to Whitby on Sundays.  (The permanent Sunday service results from 
defaultthe initiative of the CRP).  It cannot meet other demands, such as travel to
default 
defaultwork from Whitby to Middlesbrough, for example, or for longer day trips from the line to Leeds or London.  
defaultThese limited services were introduced by BR many years ago as part of 
defaulta resource-led timetable to save money, but have become embedded in the 
defaultfranchise specifications.  They severely limit the journey opportunities possible by rail and a great deal more could be achieved with a higher frequency.  As the
default lines
default serve isolated 
defaultcommunities, demand levels will always be lower than those on the busier suburban or interurban routes which will 
defaulttherefore 
defaultalways show better value for money in any 
defaultcompetition for resources
default.  However, as these lines are few in number and atypical, AcoRP 
defaultwould argue that funding and rolling st
defaultock should be made available
default, exceptionally,
default to 
defaultimprove services to the rural communities they serve, at least on a trial basis.  
defaultA number of long rural routes serving isolated commun
defaulti
defaultties in Scotland also have just 
defaultthree or four trains a day, but a positive example of tackling 
defaultthis 
defaultis currently planned
default on the West Highland line between Glasgow and Oban.  Here, through skil
defaultl
defaultful timetabling and 
defaultdiagramming
default of the Scotrail fleet
default,
default it will be possible to double the frequency between the junction at Cr
defaulti
defaultanlarich and Oban from three to six trains a day by using just one additional two-car train.  The additional cost of this is being met by Transport Scotland, but the benefits to passen
defaultgers are widespread
default,
default providing new journey opportunities, better ferry connections 
defaultto the islands 
defaultand a link with the Fort William to London sleeper.     
default&#xa0;
defaultD. 
defaultHow effectively do Community Transport services address the needs of passengers in isolated commu
defaultnities? How could Community Transport be improved?
defaultBecause of its flexibility and frequent use of accessible vehicles, Community Transport organisations can provide services that are tailored very specifically to local needs, offering a cost-effective tran
defaultsport option in rural areas.  Furthermore, their not-for-profit status and close links with the communities they serve meet the government’s localism agenda admirably.  However, as with CRP’s, reductions in local authority funding and other sources of inco
defaultme, such as BSOG, are putting the long-term future of many of these groups in doubt.  
defaultThere is no doubt that closer integration of community transport operations with community rail routes 
defaultc
defaultould be of significant benefit to rural communities and could off
defaulter greater value for money across the board.  Several Community Rail Partnerships are already experimenting with minibus links to and from their local stations and these are proving successful. 
defaultSimilarly, the Heart of Wales Line partnership runs minibuses 
defaultto bring people from the train to visit tourist attractions in the isolated communities along its route.  
defaultIt is our view however that wider introduction of this concept could only be achieved with proper financial support and encouragement through 
defaultmodifying competition legislation.
defaultACoRP fully supports community transport operations, and maintains contact with the Community Transport Association, although they are not 
defaultdirect
defaultly within our remit. 
defaultE. 
defaultTo what extent should passengers in isolated commun
defaultities be expected to rely on taxis and other demand-responsive transport services?
defaultRail is a 
defaulthigh volume
default transport mode 
defaultand
default even the smallest train of one coach has a seating capacity 
defaultfor 
default75 p
defaultassengers
default, so inevitably, some isolated communities will be bett
defaulter served by demand responsive transport services, including cars and bicycles.  The important point then is to ensure an easy transfer at the railhead with adequate car parking, secure cycle storage and good interchange 
defaultbetween
default bus, taxi
default,
default community transport
default and 
defaultrail
default.
defaultIn general, deep rural areas have few taxis available and fares will inevitably be high, simply because of the distances to be covered.  Accessibility and the cost of living in rural areas remains a deep-seated problem, and the cost of a taxi fare will fre
defaultquently outweigh the ability of someone to pay. In an urban environment, the taxi 
defaultc
defaultan 
defaultbe an affordable 
defaultoption, whereas for rural dwellers it becomes more often a distressed purchase.
default&#xa0;
defaultF. 
defaultWhat are the main challenges associated with funding transport servic
defaultes in isolated communities? How can these services be made more affordable?
defaultWith its own infrastructure and high safety and accessibility standards, rail is a relatively expensive mode, although costs are being reduced through the regulated 
defaultsettlement for 
defaultControl Period 4 involving a reduction in Network Rail costs of around a third.  At the same time, reducing franchising payments or 
defaultincreasing premia for train operators 
defaultmean that train operators 
defaultin aggregate 
defaultare 
defaultnow net contributors to Government, rather 
defaultthan a net
default cost to the taxpayer.  
defaultT
defaulthe principles of community rail 
defaultdevelopment have enabled costs savings to be made (for example the Harrington hump) but community r
defaulta
defaultil lines are generally run with minimal resources and the scope for significant further r
defaulteduction of cost is limited.  
defaultHowever, CRPs are very effective in increasing ridership which reduces the subsidy per passenger kilometre and so increases the value for money to the taxpayer of the service provided.
defaultThe Heart of Wales Line Forum is actively
default investigating whether some form of local management of their long route can be used to enhance services at low cost. They aim to have a scheme in place in time for the implementation of the new Wales and Borders franchise in 2018. They have the active sup
defaultport of Welsh Government, ORR and ACoRP in this.
